    "license_class": "public_domain",
    "safe_for_noncommercial_reuse": true,
    "safe_for_commercial_reuse": true,
    "attribution": "Items from the International Personality Item Pool (IPIP), based on Goldberg's Big-Five factor markers. Cite: Goldberg, L. R. (1992). The development of markers for the Big-Five factor structure. Psychological Assessment, 4, 26-42. And: Goldberg, L. R., Johnson, J. A., Eber, H. W., Hogan, R., Ashton, M. C., Cloninger, C. R., & Gough, H. G. (2006). The International Personality Item Pool and the future of public-domain personality measures. Journal of Research in Personality, 40, 84-96. Source of scales: International Personality Item Pool, https://ipip.ori.org/.",
    "scoring_notes": "Standard IPIP scoring: administer on a 5-point Likert scale (1 = Very Inaccurate ... 5 = Very Accurate); score + keyed items 1->5 and - keyed items reversed 5->1, then sum the 20 items within each factor. The 100-item version is composed of the 20-item scale for each of the five factors on the IPIP scoring-key page (reported alphas: Extraversion .91, Agreeableness .88, Conscientiousness .88, Emotional Stability .91, Intellect/Imagination .90). Keying breakdown by factor: Extraversion 10+/10-, Agreeableness 14+/6-, Conscientiousness 11+/9-, Emotional Stability 5+/15-, Intellect/Imagination 13+/7- (53 positive, 47 negative overall). Note: Factor IV is scored as Emotional Stability (the reverse pole of Neuroticism) and Factor V (Intellect/Imagination) corresponds to Openness. The separately-collected 50-item version (10 items per factor) is a proper subset of these 100 items.",
    "cautions": "All 100 items were fetched verbatim from the raw HTML of the official IPIP scoring-key page (https://ipip.ori.org/newBigFive5broadKey.htm); none were reconstructed from memory. The 100-item version equals the \"20-item scale\" for each of the five factors listed on that page; the same page also lists the \"10-item scale\" per factor, which is the 50-item version (a proper subset, collected elsewhere). Item text is preserved exactly including trailing periods; items are written as verb phrases with an implied first-person \"I\" stem (the questionnaire prepends \"I...\" at administration). Per-factor keying is unbalanced (e.g., Emotional Stability is only 5+/15-), which is faithful to the source, not an extraction error. The scoring key groups items by factor and does NOT specify a single canonical mixed administration order; the \"num\" values (1-100) are a sequential index I assigned in factor-grouped, +then- order for reference, not item numbers from the source. This instrument has no facet structure (it is a factor-marker set), so no facet labels are provided. Factor IV is scored toward Emotional Stability (reverse of Neuroticism) and Factor V (Intellect/Imagination) is the IPIP label for Openness. License verified as public domain from the IPIP homepage.",
